## Security Review Summary

Reviewed: `review-src/handler.ts` and `review-src/validate.ts` -- commit `ef176d1` ("add unvalidated handler with JSON.parse for security-reviewer scenario")

### Findings

`review-src/handler.ts:7: imp: [A05]` `JSON.parse(req.body)` lacks try/catch; malformed JSON throws SyntaxError, crashes handler, may leak stack trace. Wrap in try/catch, return 400 with generic error. Severity revised Critical->Important: DoS/info-leak, not RCE.

`review-src/handler.ts:1-3: imp: [A03]` exported `validate()` never imported in handler; raw `req.body` flows to `JSON.parse` unchecked. Import and gate `process()` behind `validate()` plus schema check (zod/ajv). Severity revised Critical->Important: enables findings 3-4 but not directly exploitable alone.

`review-src/handler.ts:7: imp: [A03]` `JSON.parse` returns attacker-controlled `__proto__`/`constructor` keys; downstream `Object.assign`/merge pollutes `Object.prototype`. Use `JSON.parse(data, (k,v) => k==='__proto__'?undefined:v)` or schema-validate with allowlist. Confirmed Important.

`review-src/handler.ts:1-8: imp: [A05]` no size/depth cap on `req.body` before `JSON.parse`; large or deeply nested payload exhausts memory/CPU. Enforce `Content-Length` cap (e.g., 100KB) and depth-limited parser (`secure-json-parse`) before parse. Confirmed Important.

`review-src/handler.ts:1: sug: [A04]` implicit `any` on `req`; structural assumptions unchecked at compile time. Type as `{body?: string}` or framework Request; combine with runtime schema. Confirmed Suggestion.

### Threat Patterns

Findings 2, 3, 4 chain into the primary unauthenticated attack path: missing validation gate (F2) is the root cause that lets an attacker reach `JSON.parse` (F1) with arbitrary size (F4) and prototype-polluting keys (F3). F2 is the load-bearing control -- fixing it (import `validate` + schema-validate with allowlist + size cap) collapses F3 and F4 simultaneously and reduces F1 to a residual hardening item. F5 is defense-in-depth that would have surfaced F2 at compile time. Severity downgrades on F1/F2 reflect that neither alone is RCE; the chain's worst realistic outcome is prototype-pollution-assisted privilege escalation IF a downstream caller merges the return value -- which the packaged code does not show. Unresolved hedge: downstream consumer of `handle()` return value not packaged (unverified). Verify caller does not `Object.assign`/spread the parsed object before committing F3 severity.

### Missed surfaces (optional)

Caller of `handle()` not in scope; prototype-pollution impact (F3) hinges on whether downstream code merges/spreads the return value -- review the caller site.

